The spli() - apply() - combine() pattern¶

So far in this section we have broken down our dataset into smaller chunks and we have operated on the chunks individually. This is very similar to the split() and apply() steps. What we have NOT done is : Put these two pieces together in one unified Data Structure.

The groupby() method implements all these three steps in one single operation¶

The groupby() method¶

We use groupby() to carry out a split() , apply() , combine() type of operation

  • The method splits the dataframe by the key that we provide
  • In this case 'Platform'
  • groups the data by Platform (as many groups as there are categories)
  • Then apply a function
  • And then put back the resulting output in one nice Data Structure

The DataFrame groupby() Object¶

Lets take a closer look at the output of groupby() method before the aggregate function is applied

In [78]:
sales.groupby('Platform').sum()
Out[78]:
NA_Sales EU_Sales JP_Sales Other_Sales
Platform
PS3 392.26 343.71 79.99 141.93
PS4 96.80 123.70 14.30 43.36
X360 601.05 280.58 12.43 85.54
XOne 83.19 45.65 0.34 11.92
In [79]:
sales.groupby('Platform')
Out[79]:
<pandas.core.groupby.generic.DataFrameGroupBy object at 0x00000232D33A7130>
  • We see an interesting DataFrame groupby object
  • Think of this as a special view into an intermediate output
  • At this stage Pandas has kind of split our dataset into sub-groups
  • And , is waiting for instructions as to what to do next
  • Its not into the apply step yet
  • Its not yet split also
  • Its just validated our mapping ans waiting
In [80]:
#Lets look at the len of dataframe groupby object
len(sales.groupby('Platform'))
Out[80]:
4
In [81]:
sales.Platform.unique()
Out[81]:
array(['X360', 'PS3', 'PS4', 'XOne'], dtype=object)

4 groups created for 4 categories

This concept of sitting and waiting is called "Lazy Evaluation" in computer terms : Meaning : No computation or calculation is takes place until it is needed or called for.

Key Note :¶

Applying "groupby()" on a DataFrame returns a DataFrame group by Object and not a DataFrame

Fine-Tuned Aggregates¶

Now we will look at the Aggregation function:

In pandas , all of these codes are identical:

- studios.groupby[['Genre' , 'Publisher']].sum()
- studios.groupby[['Genre' , 'Publisher']].aggregate('sum')
- studios.groupby[['Genre' , 'Publisher']].agg('sum') 
- studios.groupby[['Genre' , 'Publisher']].agg(np.sum)
In [58]:
#agg is short for aggregate

The advantage of using the aggregate() function is , it allows us to apply several functions in one go.

  • This method accepts Python list of functions as well

GroupBy Transformations¶

transform() : Applies a transformation inplace

When it is combined with groupby() gives us access to a whole new array of transforms that could be applied at the subgroup level.

For example :

As Data Scientist or Analyst we are facing a task, to convert raw global_sales to within-genre standard scores

We need to convert the global sales data from the raw sales that we have in our 'games' dataframe.

Standard score is nothing but Z-score¶

Z-Score : We take any given observation , subtract the Mean then divide by the standard Deviation and that gives us the sense of how high or low relative to its sample , any given observation is.

A Z-score is a numerical measurement that describes a value's relationship to the mean of a group of values

The Z-score, or standard score, is the number of standard deviations a given data point lies above or below the mean.

Z score or standard score describes a value's relationship to the mean of a group of values.

A z score can be defined as a measure of the number of standard deviations by which a score is below or above the mean of a distribution.

In [123]:
#Lets say that a single game sold at 5 M
game_sale = 5
#This game gave a Genre Avg
game_genre_avg = 0.5
game_genre_std = 0.1
In [125]:
#The Standard Score for this game is 45. So, this game is an Outeperformer.
Z_Score  = (game_sale - game_genre_avg)/game_genre_std
In [126]:
Z_Score
Out[126]:
45.0
  • So, we tansformed the raw sales (game_sale = 5), to 45 , which is a relatively within group outperformance of this game. It has nothing to do with 0.5 , it has everything to do with the relationship between all three :{game_sale = 5 ,game_genre_avg = 0.5 , game_genre_std = 0.1}

Lets say , we are not happy with only knowing the level of Sales, instead we also want toget the feel for how variable these sales are.

In [142]:
#Lets go and create a function for it.

Before that lets understand the Coefficient of variation: Its the ratio of Std dev and the mean

For "variability" we are using a metric called "Coeff of Variation" , also known as the relative Std deviation.

  • "volatile" if the coeff of variation is greater than 2 , else "Steady"
  • this below function returns a tuple of strings
  • return(variability , level + ' sales')
In [143]:
def sales_detail(sg):
    level = 'solid' if sg.EU_Sales.sum() > 50 else 'weak'
    variability = 'volatile' if sg.EU_Sales.std()/sg.EU_Sales.mean() > 2  else 'steady'
    return(variability , level + ' sales')
In [144]:
ps3.groupby('Genre').apply(sales_detail)
Out[144]:

  • We see that , by the criteria that we set , most Genre's in this sample have steady-weak sales and only one category has "steady solid sales" , that means , the Average game in the Genre brings in the lot of money. And also the variability across 'games' within the 'Genre' is also low.
